28:00.307 --> 28:09.475
just agricultural and stock shows and that sort of 
thing and agricultural products. They brought it

28:10.450 --> 28:27.930
into the fold of something that they could get 
involved in the community with, and they ran

28:10.450 --> 28:27.930
tractor safety programs that we designed for 
them, a double line for safety for use of seat belts

28:10.450 --> 28:27.930
and not drinking while driving. Programs were 
promulgated, all in the sense of community

28:29.132 --> 28:36.060
development in the future parts of America. The 
National Association of State Development

28:39.020 --> 29:05.702
agencies nasdaq they call it i've consulted with 
them most recently in montana helping the

28:39.020 --> 29:05.702
governor of montana put on town meetings in 11 
cities in montana which was an exciting

28:39.020 --> 29:05.702
experience it was again just people to people 
getting their views finding where there was

28:39.020 --> 29:05.702
consensus seeing how to build on the consensus and 
move on from there it's rarely a a big announcement

29:06.475 --> 29:09.518
that the world has suddenly got better. It's a lot 
of little bitty things where things improve. And

29:14.342 --> 29:23.169
you look back 10 years later and say, boy, I don't 
know whether you want to call it improved or not,

29:14.342 --> 29:23.169
but when we moved to Rockport in 1975, there was one 
traffic light in town. Now we have 11. You're going

29:26.652 --> 29:32.998
to vary as to whether the old timers don't think 
that's much improvement

29:26.652 --> 29:32.998
there. But now we're going to bypass around the 
town. we can get rid of our stoplights. You

29:39.726 --> 29:46.434
mentioned with the safety and then the traffic 
lights, some of the results here, but what were the

29:39.726 --> 29:46.434
goals that you looked at? Nate, what were the goals 
that you looked at? I mean, all the other, the hard

29:49.738 --> 29:54.603
work really notwithstanding, what were the goals 
that you were working for? What was the ideal

29:54.663 --> 29:57.667
result? Basically, it was to make our rural areas a 
better place to work, live, play, and pray. In

30:05.858 --> 30:08.162
other words, the quality of life is your goal. Why 
should the rural people have a lousy quality of

30:08.763 --> 30:11.347
life? And so I think the quality of life has 
improved considerably throughout the United

30:12.488 --> 30:32.119
States in rural areas, perhaps at a faster rate 
than in the cities, given their current

30:12.488 --> 30:32.119
propensity to crime and the underclass 
development and some almost intractable

30:33.517 --> 30:34.138
problems. Matter of fact, the thing that 
interested me the most and got me involved in rural

30:34.518 --> 30:45.992
development was we operated on a scale where you 
could make something happen and you could study

30:34.518 --> 30:45.992
the problem. When you try to do the same thing in New 
York City, Washington, D.C., Boston, that's

30:46.012 --> 30:55.764
breaking it down to neighborhoods. In rural 
areas, we put things together to build it up enough

30:55.784 --> 30:59.548
to have enough scale. In metropolitan areas, 
they've got to break it down to get it to enough

31:04.027 --> 31:07.750
scale that you can even fool with it. And then 
there's so many interacting forces that you don't

31:07.770 --> 31:11.293
have in the rural setting. So it's a lot tougher to 
solve those urban problems than it is the rural

31:11.734 --> 31:15.977
problems. They have their problems, but I'll take 
those any day over the metropolitan area. Well, I

31:21.262 --> 31:24.925
think that pretty much concludes the interview. 
Is there anything else you'd like to leave future

31:24.945 --> 31:32.852
researchers, students, and listeners to this 
interview, leave them with about rural

31:24.945 --> 31:32.852
development? Well, I guess if a guy with as little 
formal training as I had, and

31:34.267 --> 31:50.228
I didn't realize this at the time, but I just had a 
tremendous opportunity to learn. And I learned

31:51.129 --> 31:52.952
from so many people. I didn't learn how to do a 
regression analysis, but I never had to do one. I

31:59.140 --> 32:03.025
had people that worked for me who could do a 
regression analysis. so many things in life where

32:03.646 --> 32:25.102
you need the technical knowledge, but there are 
other things you need, some other kind of skills to

32:03.646 --> 32:25.102
put the technical knowledge to work, to get people 
to work together on it, so that two brains are

32:03.646 --> 32:25.102
better than one, maybe equivalent to three. You 
know, you're not limited by the zero-sums game in

32:27.338 --> 32:29.100
development. You always increase the size of the 
pie rather than define how you divide it, which

32:29.160 --> 32:40.175
traditional economic models apply. I don't know 
whether you remember Leon Tiff or not, the guy who

32:40.195 --> 32:44.942
invented input-output models. Well, I 
participated on a panel he chaired in the Senate

32:46.243 --> 32:57.278
for a hearing, and everybody up there except me had 
Ph.D.s in economics. But I raised questions. If

